     <strong><cite class="fn">JG</cite></strong><br>

      
      <p>An interesting and thoughtful article, thank you. I&#039;ve a comment on the corkage fee. There are very good reasons to bring in your own wine. Basically, the restaurant makes a huge profit on something it didn&#039;t make, and whose quality it can only harm by improper storage. Many customers know very well what taste they like with their food. They may have special varieties or wineries they like. Having a customer bring a familiar taste with them to the table is certain to improve the customer&#039;s perception of the food quality.</p>
<p>If a customer has a sophisticated palate, the chances are good they have better taste than the restaurant does, or that the restaurant buyer has. The very best deals in a restaurant&#039;s wine are likely to be gone, and what&#039;s left grossly overpriced. If I was having a special dinner? I&#039;d absolutely bring my own wine. It might very well end up being cheaper and better.</p>

