     <div class="commentItem" id="comment-545888">
     <strong><cite class="fn">The Truth</cite></strong><br>

      
      <p>You will find that charge in a lot of countries, especially around the Mediterranean.  We have that cost in America too, but it is rolled up in the price of the food.  In many countries laws require that service be a separate charge from the food.  The logic being the server, dishwasher, busboy, etc are not involved in the making of the food so the restaurant can not legally include their cost in the food.  Other countries may not have a law requiring it but restaurants still break out the charge out of tradition.  Whether the charge is rolled up in the food price or broken out separately the total bill is still going to be the same price.  If you think its an unnecssary charge, its only because its an itemized charge you can see.  In America its out of sight out of mind.  Hopefully you did not tip American style.  In Greece tipping is not obligatory and done for good service, typically 10%.</p>

