<ul class="children">
   <li class="comment byuser comment-author-laserw odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-545017">
     <div class="commentItem" id="comment-545017">
     <strong><cite class="fn"><a href='http://laserw.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>laserw</a></cite></strong><br>

      
      <p>As a former corporate Wendy&#039;s manager, that never was ever the policy &#8211; some franchise may have charged extra for toppings, but that was never a Wendy&#039;s policy with one exception &#8211; tomatoes.   I date back to 1981 and at that time tomatoes did cost extra &#8211; and so did cheese &#8211; when back was added a year or so later, that became an extra topping.    But I can emphatically defend Wendy&#039;s &#8211; that was never a corporate policy &#8211; maybe in some urban areas where costs to operate are outrageous, but I&#039;ve never heard of such a thing and I had nearly 20 years with the company.</p>
<p>I left Wendy&#039;s in 1997 and now will refuse to eat there because the quality and service is horrible and every product that I loved when I worked for them has been ruined &#8211; everything from the burgers, the buns, the frostys (which should never be anything but chocolate) to those disgusting fries.   So I have no reason to defend Wendy&#039;s other than corporate restaurants are run differently than franchises &#8211; I know &#8211; I went to work for a franchise for a couple of months and they know it all &#8211; they think they can do their own thing and they don&#039;t even follow procedures that I knew like the back of my hand (I was a training store manager).</p>

