      <p>The point is not that we shouldn&#039;t be compassionate towards less fortunate individuals.  The issue here is that just one seemingly low paying, tough profession alone cannot be nursed by other people.  Compassion is one thing and demand that you pay a certain amount because they took a low paying job is another.  The waitstaff complain about how bad it is with the job, the employer, the IRS etc.  But, instead of fighting with them for a change, they are pushing the customers to compensate.  I&#039;m all for better wages i.e. fed min wage regardless of the tip that people give them.  If paying them fed min wage pushes the price of the food, so be it.  But, it cannot be &#034;they don&#039;t pay me well.  So, you HAVE TO pay me at least 20% of the check amount&#034;.  That&#039;s ridiculous.  Social responsibility should be towards ALL people whose wages are low and are providing a service.  So, let&#039;s start tipping McDonald&#039;s workers, the garbage collectors, the street sweepers etc.  I&#039;m sure garbage collection is much more strenuous a job.</p>

