      <p>The reality is that nothing in a restaurant can be free &#8211; not even the bathrooms, because all of these things cost the owner real money. Americans have long been accustomed to &#034;bundled&#034; pricing, in airlines (&#034;free&#034; checked bags and meals) restaurants (&#034;free&#034; bread and coffee refills). In other parts of the world, unbundled pricing is more common. Bundled pricing typically leads to higher consumer prices since people use the &#034;free&#034; goods and services whether or not they would otherwise have purchased them.</p>

