      <p>Very well written article. I have been a chef, with an involvement in the food industry for my whole life and completely agree with most of what you say. The hidden costings in setting up and running a catering business/ restaurant, not to mention the rise in the cost of ingredients and transportation have forced the industry to squeeze pennies out of every place possible &#8211; sad truth. However, I am souly referring to the characteristics of a small/ private business within this economical climate. The slightly more corporate side of this argument is an absolute joke, for example McDonalds charging extra for ketchup &#8211; do they really not make enough money already? £6-£7 for a large burger, chips and a drink that would cost no more that 80p for a corporation of that size to put together. It&#039;s a real shocker that they can even get away with it &#8211; what&#039;s to come in the future? A breathing fee?</p>

