      <p>Splitting the check can be costly to the business because, take someone like myself who eats out with friends at the local wing joint.  You have a table of 10 people (no fixed gratuity) splitting a check 8 ways, that can be up to 8 credit card runs.  And it takes the server about 10-15 minutes to distribute the checks, collect the checks, run all of the tabs, make change (for the cash people), redistribute the final check, etc. which means she can&#039;t serve her other tables.  On the up side, people tend to tip better in larger groups with split tabs.  If my meal cost me $6, I feel bad about leaving any less than $2 and change, which is a 33% tip.  Most people tip high on smaller amounts.  On larger amounts, I pretty much stick to the 15% rule, give or take the individual.</p>

